  monumentInformation:
    monumentInformation:
    - title: Who Built It
      details:
      - The Taj Mahal was commissioned by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in memory of
        his wife Mumtaz Mahal, who died during childbirth.
      - The main architect of the Taj Mahal was Ustad Ahmad Lahori, who led a team
        of skilled artisans and workers from various regions.
    - title: Where It Is Located
      details:
      - The Taj Mahal is located in Agra, a historic city in Uttar Pradesh, India,
        which was a significant city during the Mughal Empire.
      - The mausoleum stands on the southern bank of the Yamuna River, enhancing
        its scenic beauty with its reflection in the water.
    - title: When It Was Built
      details:
      - Construction of the Taj Mahal began in 1632, shortly after the death of Mumtaz
        Mahal, and involved over 20,000 workers.
      - The entire structure, including its surrounding complex, was completed in
        1653, taking approximately 21 years to finish.
    - title: How It Is Protected
      details:
      - The Taj Mahal became a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983, recognised for
        its cultural and architectural significance.
      - It is protected and maintained by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI),
        which ensures its preservation and upkeep.
    - title: Why It Was Built
      details:
      - Shah Jahan built the Taj Mahal as a mausoleum for Mumtaz Mahal, symbolising
        his deep love and grief after her death.
      - The monument was intended to stand as a symbol of eternal love and to immortalise
        the grandeur of the Mughal Empire's architectural achievements.
